<h3>Problem Scenario</h3>

<p>
	<u>Starting turn</u> - Sam and his friends are about halfway through a game. It’s Sam’s turn again and he begins strategizing where to attack next. He immediately goes to grab troops, completely forgetting he has resource cards to turn in for a red star. By the time he realizes this he’s already placed his troops and begun expanding; it’s too late for him to go back. Frustrated, he hopes that no one else finds a way to win before he’s able to get that red star his next turn. 
</p>
<p>
	<u>Recruit Troops</u> - Sam needs to recruit troops next. He quickly counts up the number of territories he controls, remembers to add in cities, and divides by three to get his troops. He places them in Southeast Asia, ready to attack Australia. Halfway through his turn his friend asks “Wait, did you get your North America continent bonus?” Everyone has to stop as they try to remember. Eventually they try to estimate how many turns have gone by since Sam got North America and keep playing. There’s so many different bonuses and every game someone misses at least one.
</p>
<p>
	<u>Ending turn</u> - It’s finally the end of Sam’s turn. Despite the confusion with his troops he’s managed to conquer Indonesia and Western Australia. He remembers to grab a coin card. He sits back and passes the dice to his friend. Unfortunately Sam has forgotten about the scar card in Iceland which gives him an extra troop at the end of every turn.
</p>


<h3>Usability Requirements</h3>

<p>
	The first requirement is to store information about the game so that the user does not need to remember it. The information must then be displayed to the user in a way that helps to remind them of certain actions to take.
</p>

<p>
	The other requirement for the application is to balance the amount of information stored with staying out of the way of the actual game. The more information stored the more help we can give to user, but in order to get that information the user must stop playing to enter it. Limiting the breaks in play while maximizing help to the player will be very important.
</p>

